        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "refactor(memory): drop redundant agent-id scoping from qmd collection names",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- **What:** drop the redundant `-<agentId>` scoping from managed qmd collection names. Each agent has its **own isolated qmd index** (`agents/<agentId>/qmd/index.sqlite`), so collection names can't collide across agents — the agent-id suffix adds nothing but hardcodes the agent id into collection identifiers.\n- **How:** remove `scopeCollectionBase` (and two now-dead path helpers, `isPathInsideRoot` / `canonicalizePathForContainment`); name default collections by their base (`memory-root`, `memory-dir`), the session collection `sessions`, and extra collections by their explicit name. Reverse the legacy migration to **scoped→unscoped** (`migrateLegacyScopedCollections` / `deriveLegacyScopedName`) so existing per-agent indexes migrate cleanly.\n- **Why migration is cheap:** qmd collections are a **rebuildable derived index** (not user data), so the migration drops the stale scoped collection and lets the unscoped one be (re)created + reindexed — no import, no data loss (consistent with this repo's \"prefer delete/drop/rebuild over import for cache\").\n- **Outcome:** stable, agent-agnostic collection names; net **−56 LOC** for the de-scope itself (removes the scoping helper + a path-containment branch).\n- **Stacked on #91253 (per ClawSweeper):** the first commit is the path-aware qmd-rebind fix (#91253); the second is the de-scope. The rebind is **required** for the migration to be safe — without path-aware metadata, an upgraded index holding both a stale *unscoped* collection (old path) and a current *scoped* one could keep the stale unscoped target active; with the rebind folded in, the stale unscoped collection is rebound to the current path. Once #91253 lands, this rebases to just the de-scope commit.\n\n## Linked context\n\nCloses #91259\n\nDepends on / folds in #91253 (path-aware qmd collection rebind) — the first commit of this PR.\n\nRelated: #91265 (an earlier PR toward the same proposal; this one folds in the path-aware rebind so existing scoped indexes migrate safely, adds an upgrade-case regression, and includes live before/after behavior proof).\n\nRequested by a maintainer or owner? No — follows from the proposal in #91259.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\nBehavior addressed: managed qmd collection names dropping the redundant `-<agentId>` suffix, with existing scoped per-agent indexes migrating to the unscoped names.\n\nReal environment tested: a live, self-hosted OpenClaw gateway (macOS), memory backend `qmd` (`@tobilu/qmd` 2.5.2), running this build, against an agent whose index already held scoped collections.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch:\n```\n# build the gateway with this change, restart, then force a reindex of an agent\n# whose qmd index already holds scoped collections:\nopenclaw gateway restart\nopenclaw memory index --force --agent <agent>\nsqlite3 <agent-qmd-index>.sqlite \"select name,path from store_collections order by name;\"\n```\n\nEvidence after fix (live gateway, identifiers redacted):\n```\n# BEFORE (existing index, scoped names):\nmemory-root-<agent>   <WS>\nmemory-dir-<agent>    <WS>/memory\nsessions-<agent>      <agent-state>/qmd/sessions\nteam-library-<agent>  <WS>/library/promoted\nteam-library          <WS-old>/library/promoted   # orphan duplicate\n\n# AFTER (this patch, reindex):\nmemory-root    <WS>\nmemory-dir     <WS>/memory\nsessions       <agent-state>/qmd/sessions\nteam-library   <WS>/library/promoted\n# scoped (-<agent>) collections remaining: 0\n```\n\nObserved result after fix: all managed collections migrated to unscoped names; `0` scoped collections remained; the prior orphan duplicate (`team-library` + `team-library-<agent>`) collapsed to a single `team-library`.\n\nWhat was not tested: a fresh (never-scoped) index — covered by unit tests (default + custom collection names assert the unscoped form); and sandbox/container-mode end-to-end.\n\nProof limitations or environment constraints: live evidence is redacted terminal output from a private fleet (paths/agent/team identifiers removed).\n\nBefore evidence: shown inline above (the pre-reindex scoped names + orphan duplicate).\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nCommands run (clean checkout off `openclaw/openclaw` `main`):\n- `pnpm test extensions/memory-core/src/memory` → **433 passed (40 files)**\n- `pnpm test packages/memory-host-sdk` → **38 passed (9 files)**\n- `pnpm check:test-types` (tsgo) → **clean, 0 errors**\n- `oxfmt` applied to the touched files.\n\nRegression coverage:\n- Default + custom collection-name tests now assert the unscoped form.\n- The unscoped→scoped migration tests were replaced with scoped→unscoped ones, plus a migration-guard regression (a scoped collection whose path does not match the desired collection is skipped, not clobbered).\n- **Upgrade-case regression (addresses the flagged compatibility risk):** an index holding BOTH a stale *unscoped* collection (old path) AND a current *scoped* one at the name switch → asserts the stale unscoped collection is rebound to the **current** path (via the folded-in `collection show` path enrichment), not left active.\n\nMulti-agent note: safe by construction — each agent has its own isolated qmd index, so unscoped names cannot collide across agents.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nUser-visible behavior change? Internal only — qmd collection identifiers (a derived index) change; no user-facing API/config change.\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? Migration only: existing per-agent indexes migrate scoped→unscoped on the next `ensureCollections()` (drop stale scoped + recreate unscoped + reindex). No config keys changed.\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? No.\n\nHighest-risk area: the scoped→unscoped migration on existing indexes.\n\nHow is that risk mitigated: the migration only acts when the legacy **scoped** collection exists AND matches the desired collection's path/pattern (guarded by `canMigrate...`); otherwise it is skipped. qmd collections are rebuildable, so a dropped-then-recreated collection reindexes with no data loss.\n\n## Current review state\n\nNext action: maintainer review.\n\nWhat is still waiting: CI + review.\n\nWhich bot or reviewer comments were addressed: none (initial submission).\n",
